t2195.text: When they get drunk, they shout a lot. I won’t going to detail but I have weirdly specific trauma around being near shouting drunk men. Oh and there was so much noise so I nearly went into sensory overload. Needless to say, I bailed early. I wanted to stay but it was too hard.

t2196.text: Uncle Stephen just couldn’t resist making another comment about my weight and I snapped at him. I said: “mate! I get you’re having a hard time but you need to stop with those comments.” I shouldn’t have but I lost it. Oh and everybody there was drunk.

t2197.text: You really are selfish people. Oh and Doreen has an equally selfish son called Wayne. He spent the entire funeral talking to anyone who would listen about how amazing he was. After that, we went to the wake and it wasn’t much better.

t2198.text: Terry and the other sister Doreen hate each other so to them, it was just a competition. They were trying to see who could act the saddest. I found that disgusting and disrespectful. You never had time for us and now you use our grief as a way to compete with each other?

t2199.text: Gran has another really selfish sister who did the same thing. She hasn’t been in our lives for years but she put on a big performance. She could’ve won an Oscar because she was such a good actress. They weren’t genuinely sad though.

t2200.text: Remember Cindy was the one who sent the passive aggressive text about her mum being best friends with Gran. I found out today that they weren’t best friends at all. Gran hated her. Cindy and her parents Dawn and Terry showed up and made a big performance of how sad they were.

t2201.text: How on earth do you know me? I’ve never met you in my entire life. Mum says she doesn’t know you and dad hasn’t seen you since he was a child. I didn’t talk to her for very long but Cindy strikes me as a very selfish person. Her and both her parents are.

t2202.text: Oh and on top of all that, we had a family drama because apparently we just can’t get enough of that. So cousin Cindy showed up today and it’s the first time I’ve ever met her. She was acting all friendly and joking with me like she knew me for years.

t2203.text: I know it’s a horrible thing to joke about but it was easier to pretend it was. I don’t think I was quite ready to admit to myself that she was really gone. Reality caught up with me when I saw them carrying the coffin in.

t2204.text: That was bad!!! We had the funeral today and those are never fun. This might sound ridiculous but part of me kept thinking she wasn’t really gone. I thought it was just a cruel joke and someone would eventually admit it.
